data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". Use MSTest's specialized collection assertions instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

Key changes:

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Shows "collection was empty" vs generic "was false" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows "expected 3, got N" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | Remove — `Single()` already throws if missing | Redundant check |

The `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` line is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API, so `IsTrue` is appropriate there.

Also consider sealing the test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance, per MSTest best practices.
